<!--
  wazuh-home (manager): logall_json setting.

  Add this single line inside the existing <global> block in
  /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf on the manager VM. Example resulting block:

      <global>
        <jsonout_output>yes</jsonout_output>
        <alerts_log>yes</alerts_log>
        <logall_json>yes</logall_json>     <-- this is the addition
        <email_notification>no</email_notification>
        ...
      </global>

  Why: Wazuh's default behaviour writes only ALERTS (level >=3) to
  alerts.json. Everything decoded at level 0 (e.g. the catch-all DNS
  rule 100250 in manager-rules.xml) is silently dropped after decoding.

  logall_json:yes makes the manager additionally write every decoded
  event to /var/ossec/logs/archives/archives.json regardless of level.
  That's how the Vault VM DNS event stream becomes searchable on disk:
    - rule 100250 (level 0): visible in archives.json, not alerts.json
    - rule 100251 (level 3, resolved):              visible in both
    - rule 100252 (level 6, Pi-hole policy block):  visible in both
    - rule 100253 (level 4, upstream no-answer):    visible in both

  TWO-PART REQUIREMENT for dashboard visibility of archives:

  This setting only writes to disk. To also see archives in the
  Wazuh dashboard's wazuh-archives-4.x-* index (so you can filter
  rule.id=100250 there for catch-all events instead of grepping
  archives.json on the manager by hand), filebeat needs the wazuh
  archives module enabled too. Default is OFF; flip in
  /etc/filebeat/filebeat.yml under filebeat.modules:

      - module: wazuh
        alerts:
          enabled: true
        archives:
          enabled: true     # <-- change this from false to true

  Then `sudo systemctl restart filebeat`. The index pattern appears
  in the dashboard data-source picker within seconds.

  Trade-offs of enabling both halves:
    - archives.json on disk grows fast (one line per decoded event).
      Wazuh's default logrotate config under /etc/logrotate.d/wazuh
      handles rotation; check `du -sh /var/ossec/logs/archives/`
      after a few days to confirm it's bounded.
    - The wazuh-archives-* index in the indexer also grows fast.
      Set up ILM (or manually delete old indices) eventually so the
      indexer doesn't fill up.

  After editing /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf, restart the manager:
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager
-->

<logall_json>yes</logall_json>
